Below are practical detections you can deploy immediately for the type of C2 / fintech-focused hunting we discussed. I’ll structure them so they’re usable for MDE (KQL) and also easy to translate into Splunk / Google SecOps logic.

The goal is behavioral detections, not attribution. Even though groups like APT33, APT34, APT35, and MuddyWater use these patterns, the detections will catch any actor using the technique.

1️⃣ Detection: PowerShell Download Cradle (High Fidelity)
Why
Attackers frequently execute payloads using PowerShell web downloads.

KQL (MDE)
DeviceProcessEvents
| where TimeGenerated > ago(14d)
| where FileName =~ "powershell.exe" or FileName =~ "pwsh.exe"
| where ProcessCommandLine has_any (
    "downloadstring",
    "invoke-webrequest",
    "invoke-restmethod",
    "frombase64string",
    "iex ",
    "iwr ",
    "irm "
)
| project
    TimeGenerated,
    DeviceName,
    AccountName,
    FileName,
    ProcessCommandLine,
    InitiatingProcessFileName
| order by TimeGenerated desc
Detection Logic
PowerShell executing web download + execution patterns
2️⃣ Detection: Non-Browser Access to Social Media APIs (C2)
This aligns with the social media C2 hunt your team mentioned.

KQL
DeviceNetworkEvents
| where TimeGenerated > ago(14d)
| where RemoteUrl has_any (
    "api.telegram.org",
    "discord.com/api",
    "raw.githubusercontent.com",
    "pastebin.com",
    "api.github.com"
)
| where InitiatingProcessFileName !in~ ("chrome.exe","msedge.exe","firefox.exe","brave.exe")
| summarize hits=count(),
    first_seen=min(TimeGenerated),
    last_seen=max(TimeGenerated)
by DeviceName, InitiatingProcessFileName, RemoteUrl
| order by hits desc
Detection Logic
System utility contacting social media API
Very strong indicator if:

powershell
cmd
python
wscript
cscript
3️⃣ Detection: Direct IP HTTP Connections
Malware often avoids DNS and connects directly to IPs.

KQL
DeviceNetworkEvents
| where TimeGenerated > ago(14d)
| where RemoteIPType == "Public"
| where RemoteUrl == ""
| where InitiatingProcessFileName !in~ ("chrome.exe","msedge.exe","firefox.exe")
| summarize connections=count()
by DeviceName, InitiatingProcessFileName, RemoteIP
| order by connections desc
Detection Logic
Non-browser process making direct external IP connections
4️⃣ Detection: Possible C2 Beaconing
Beaconing usually appears as repeated connections to the same domain.

KQL
DeviceNetworkEvents
| where TimeGenerated > ago(7d)
| summarize
    connections=count(),
    first_seen=min(TimeGenerated),
    last_seen=max(TimeGenerated)
by DeviceName, RemoteUrl, InitiatingProcessFileName
| where connections > 50
| order by connections desc
Detection Logic
High number of connections from a single host to one domain
5️⃣ Detection: Suspicious PowerShell Encoding
Encoded PowerShell is extremely common in attacker tradecraft.

KQL
DeviceProcessEvents
| where TimeGenerated > ago(14d)
| where FileName =~ "powershell.exe"
| where ProcessCommandLine has_any ("-enc", "-encodedcommand", "frombase64string")
| project
    TimeGenerated,
    DeviceName,
    AccountName,
    ProcessCommandLine
| order by TimeGenerated desc
6️⃣ Detection: Office Spawning Script Engines
Initial access often comes from malicious documents.

